Passwords: higher security for your account 
- You can allow your IAM user change their own passwords 
- Require to change their passwords after time ( expiration ) 
- Prevent password re-use 
- In production SSO mostly used as its more secure 



Multi Factor Authentication: password you know + security device you own 

- adds secondary layer of security to your root user / IAM user 
- If password compromised account is fine as MFA requires a second fact ( device to authenticate ) 

MFA options in AWS =  Virtual MFA device - google authenticator - multiple tokens 
- Universal 2nd factor security key (UTF) - support for root & IAM users with single security key 
- Hardware key fob MFA device 
- Hardware key FOB MFA Device for AWS GovCloud



 
IAM roles

IAM user -> get permissions via policies 

IAM roles for services -> temporary credentials where a ( user , aws service , application ) can “assume ” a role a temporarily receive its permissions 

- Ex. ->  EC2 instance running on flask app and it needs to read an S3 bucket =  youattach IAM role to the EC2 instance , instead of hardcoding access keys 

IAM security Tools  -> Help monitor and strengthen access controls 

- IAM access advisior  = identifies roles/resources that have been shared outside your account + when last accessed (user-level)
- (Bonus)= setting service control policies for AWS organisations as guardrails for multiple accounts 

- IAM Credentials report (account level)
-  Shows when account users and their status of their various credentials were accessed 


IAM guidelines and best practices 
- Don’t use root user except for AWS account set up 
- Assin users to groups and give permission that way 
- Strong password and MFA 
- Use IAM roles for services 
- Use access keys for AWS SDK 
- Audit permission with AWS credentials report and AWS access analyser 
- Don’t share IAM keys or users 



User policy attach to a user group & role can be attached to services




How can you Access AWS? 
1. AWS Management console (protecter by password +MFA )
2. AWS command line interface (CLI ) - protected by access keys 
3. AWS software developer Kit ( SDK ) - for code : protected by access keys 

Access Keys -> generated through AWS console -> best practice to rotate and switch them 
- Users manage their own keys 
- Access keys are like secrets you can’t share them 

Access key ID = username 
Secret Access Key = password 


What is AWS CLI ? -> run commands through CLI to manage AWS resources 
- Helps you interact with aws service through the terminal  - aws login 
- Can do everything you can do in the aws management console 
- Lets you interact using commands in your command line shell
- Aws configure - access keys 
- (Check if your logged in) - aws sts get-caller-identitiy 
- aws iam list-users 

What is the AWS SDK - software developer kit 
- Tools for developers that helps your code talk to AWS services 
- SDK gives ready made functions , classes and methods to add to your code ( python , java etc ) to interact with AWS 
- Like spin up an EC2 or upload files to an S3 
- Ex. - python SDK = botos3 

